The Senate on Thursday urged the Federal Government to formulate policy to integrate Almajiris into the educational system to discourage them from begging on streets. The call followed a motion by Senator Sankara Abdullahi and 26 other senators on the menace of street begging and the need to rehabilitate street beggars. Abdullahi in his lead debate said begging in Nigeria appears to be intractable and overwhelming as beggars are now found everywhere. READ ALSO:Â Xenophobia: South Africa, Nigeria mend relations, sign 30 trade deals He said street begging does not only affect the geographical and social structure of urban areas, but it also portrays the country in a bad light to tourists and foreign investors. He said street begging, had become a worrisome socio-economic challenge in addition to being a serious menace and liability on the Nigerian populace. He said the phenomenon takes a heavy toll on the lives of teenagers, who engage in the act and are therefore are out of school. Senators, who spoke on the motion described street begging as a major challenge. The senate, therefore, called on the federal government to set up vocational training centres to provide beggars with alternative means of livelihood thereby making them useful to the society. (NAN)